Boil a large #pot{} of salted water for the @diced butternut squash{1}(diced).

> If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

When boiling, add the butternut squash and cook until fork tender, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%pack} in a #sieve{}.

Meanwhile, pop the @couscous{100%grams} in a #bowl{}. Pour in 200ml boiling water (500ml for 4p). Stir through half the @korma curry paste{1%sachet}. Cover with a #plate{} or #cling film{} and leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Place a large pan over a medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}. When hot, add the chickpeas and toss for ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add the @ras-el-hanout{1%sachet} and remaining korma paste. Fry for another ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @chopped tomato with onion & garlic{1%pack}, @peanut butter{1%sachet} and two-thirds of the @coconut milk{1%pack}. Cover and simmer for ~{8-10%minutes}. Stir occasionally and add a splash of @?water{to taste} to loosen the sauce if required.

Drain the butternut and stir into the stew. Season to taste with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and @sugar{to taste}.

Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{} and season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide couscous between bowls, top with the stew and garnish with @peanuts{20%grams} and a swirl of remaining coconut milk.